<subSubSection id="7C866506E6257D57EEFEDFF387B8FEDC" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="97" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="3423368DE6257D57EEFEDFF387B8FEDC" blockId="1.[151,1437,1957,2017]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,319]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="97" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis id="06E8EA9FE6257D54EEFEDFF387CBF85E" bold="true" box="[199,449,1957,1981]" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Ecology &amp; behaviour.</emphasis>
Adults were mostly observed in localities with willow, feeding on the willow sap whereas few were found feeding on rotten fig fruit (
<figureCitation id="ACA72A08E6257D54EC5BDF9F84BCF802" box="[610,694,1993,2017]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1769]" captionTargetId="figure-27@4.[151,1436,181,1769]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ecology and behaviour: A, sap feeding; B–C, territoriality; D, courtship; E mating pair." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404846" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404846/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
) in conformity with the earlier studies (
<bibRefCitation id="500D4B7CE6257D54EA65DF9F839AF802" author="McAlpine, D. K. &amp; Shatalkin, A. I." box="[1116,1424,1993,2017]" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" pagination="155 - 163" refId="ref2074" refString="McAlpine, D. K. &amp; Shatalkin, A. I. (1998) Family Pseudopomyzidae. In: Papp, L. &amp; Darvas, B. (Eds), Contributions to a Manual of Palaearctic Diptera. Vol. 3. Higher Brachycera. Science Herald, Budapest, pp 155 - 163." type="book chapter" year="1998">McAlpine &amp; Shatalkin 1998</bibRefCitation>
). The flies demonstrated strong territoriality and chased away other insects trying to feed on the sap by raising both wings e.g., drosophilid flies, lauxaniid flies, muscid flies, and ants (
<figureCitation id="ACA72A08E6267D57ED79D8ED85B2FF37" box="[832,952,187,212]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1769]" captionTargetId="figure-27@4.[151,1436,181,1769]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ecology and behaviour: A, sap feeding; B–C, territoriality; D, courtship; E mating pair." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404846" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404846/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="97">Fig. 4B–C</figureCitation>
). During courtship 
<specimenCount id="229AFD04E6267D57EAA9D8EA830EFF30" box="[1168,1284,187,211]" pageId="2" pageNumber="97" type="male">two males</specimenCount>
, in almost all the observed cases, followed the female (
<figureCitation id="ACA72A08E6267D57EC6ED88984A6FF1B" box="[599,684,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1769]" captionTargetId="figure-27@4.[151,1436,181,1769]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ecology and behaviour: A, sap feeding; B–C, territoriality; D, courtship; E mating pair." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404846" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404846/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="97">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
) and only one of them mated successfully (
<figureCitation id="ACA72A08E6267D57EABED88982D6FF1B" box="[1159,1244,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1792,1816]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1769]" captionTargetId="figure-27@4.[151,1436,181,1769]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ecology and behaviour: A, sap feeding; B–C, territoriality; D, courtship; E mating pair." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404846" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404846/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="97">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
). Male opponents approaching the female exhibited aggression by raising both wings, and expressed offensive actions such as tapping, lunging, and head-butting.
</paragraph>
